}{\plain \fs24 \f1 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b\f1 133-140.}{\plain \fs24 \f1   The protagonist's ignorance of Gherardo's virtues offers Marco (and the poet) a \softline
chance to replay the theme of the moment, that things are not what they used to be.  The early \softline
commentators are uncertain whether or not the mention of Gaia is meant to be to her praise or \softline
blame.  Jacopo della Lana (comm. to verse 140) and Benvenuto (comm. to vv. 139-140) say she \softline
was well known as a loose woman.  However, Benvenuto's self-proclaimed student, John of \softline
Serravalle, who generally supports his }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 maestro}{\plain \fs24 \f1 's opinions, has only good to speak of her (and \softline
even claims that she wrote vernacular poetry -- [comm. to vv.139-141]).  Most modern \softline
commentators argue that, since the argument at hand is that the old times bore at least some \softline
notable virtue while the present day is leaden in that respect, it would only make sense for Gaia's 
name to represent a descent from virtue.  The meaning of the clause 's'io nol togliessi da sua figlia \softline
Gaia' (unless / I were to take one [a nickname] from his daughter, Gaia) is, however, problematic.  \softline
According to Torraca (comm. to vv. 139-149) his sobriquet would then be 'il gaio' (the merry) in \softline
recognition of his courtly actions and style of being; there is probably no better positive reading of \softline
the verse than this one.  If we wish to insist on the logically more promising negative force of this \softline
line, the same descriptive phrase (now only meaning 'the father of Gaia') would have the effect of \softline
showing how the virtues of the father were not found in the daughter.  While the logic of this \softline
entire sequence calls for such a reading, the feeling in the line would seem to support Torraca's \softline
currently unfavored reading.  As several commentators suggest, until such time as some clearer \softline
evidence for Dante's opinion of Gaia is unearthed, it is impossible to be sure of the tone of the \softline
reference, wholehearted or ironic.  The only two other uses of the word }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 gaio}{\plain \fs24 \f1  in the poem are, \softline
however, totally positive: see }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 Paradiso}{\plain \fs24 \f1  XV.60 and XXVI.102.  Nonetheless, in verse 121 Dante \softline
has Marco refer to only three old men still alive in Lombardy who are good.  Since Gaia did not \softline
die until 1311, would she not have to be considered a }{\plain \fs24 \i\f1 fourth}{\plain \fs24 \f1  good Lombard (and thus not to be \softline
included)?  Or, as a woman, is she not allowed inclusion in the paltry list of the virtuous?\par
